########################### List Methods  ########################

# append(): in python, list contains append() method. it is used to add an element at the end of the list. It does not return any value. 
#in java, if list uses add() method to add an element at the end of the list. It returns true if the element is added successfully, otherwise it returns false.

# insert(): in python, list contains insert() method to insert an element at a specific index in the list. It takes two arguments, the first argument is the index at which the element needs to be inserted and the second argument is the element that needs to be inserted. same as java.
# but if the index specified to insert the element is larger than the size of the list, then the element will be inserted at the end of the list. if the index specified to insert the element is negative, then the element will be inserted at the beginning of the list.
# in java, if the index specified to insert the element is larger than the size of the list, then it will throw IndexOutOfBoundsException. if the index specified to insert the element is negative, then it will throw IndexOutOfBoundsException.

# extend(): in python, we have extend() method to add the characters of one string to another string. It is used to add the characters of one string to another string. It takes a string as an argument and adds the characters of that string to the end of the original string. 
# java does not have extend() method to add the characters of one string to another string.

# count():in python, list contains count() method. it is used to count the number of occurrences of an element in the list. It returns the count of the element in the list.if not present it returns 0.
#in java, if list uses Collections.frequency() method to count the number of occurrences of an element in the list. It returns the count of the element in the list. if not present it returns 0.

# index(): in python, list contains index() method. it is used to find the index of the first occurrence of an element in the list. It raises ValueError if the element is not found in the list. 
#in java, if list uses indexOf() method to find the index of the first occurrence of an element in the list. It returns -1 if the element is not found in the list. lastIndexOf() method is used to find the index of the last occurrence of an element in the list. It also returns -1 if the element is not found in the list.

# remove(): in python, list contains remove() method. it is used to remove the first occurrence of an element from the list. It raises ValueError if the element is not found in the list.
# in java, if list uses remove() method to remove the first occurrence of an element from the list. It returns true if the element is removed successfully, otherwise it returns false.

# pop(): in python, list contains pop() method.
# pop(index): it is used to remove an element from the list based on the specified index. It takes an index as an argument and removes the element at that index from the list. It returns the removed element. and It raises IndexError if the index is out of range.
# If the index is not specified, then it removes the last element from the list and returns it.  if the list and empty and we try to pop an element from the list, then it raises ValueError.
# in java, if list uses remove() method to remove an element from the list based on the specified index. It returns the removed element. It throws IndexOutOfBoundsException if the index is out of range. If the index is not specified, then it removes the last element from the list and returns it. if the list is empty and we try to remove an element from the list, then it throws NoSuchElementException.

# clear(): in python, list contains clear() method. it is used to remove all the elements from the list. It does not return any value.
# in java, if list uses clear() method to remove all the elements from the list.

# reverse(): in python, list contains reverse() method. reverse() method is only applicable to lists. we cant use it on other collections. It is used to reverse the order of the elements in the list in the same list, it wont create a new list and It does not return any value.
# in java, if list uses Collections.reverse() method to reverse the order of the elements in the list.

# reversed(): in python contains built-in function reversed() method. reversed() method is applicable to all the collections. It is used to reverse the order of the elements in the list and it returns a reverse iterator which needs to be casted to list after. It does not modify the original list.

# sort(): in python, list contains sort() method. it is used to sort the elements of the list in ascending order. It does not return any value. It modifies the original list. It raises TypeError if the elements of the list are not comparable/heterogeneous.
# in java, if list uses Collections.sort() method to sort the elements of the list in ascending order. It modifies the original list. It throws ClassCastException if the elements of the list are not comparable/heterogeneous.
# eg. list1.sort() --> ascending order
# list2.sort(reverse=True) --> descending order
# eg. list=[1,2,3,"a"] --> it will raise TypeError in python and ClassCastException in java because we cannot compare integer and string.

# sorted(): in python, sorted() method is a built-in function. it is used to sort the elements of the list in ascending order. It returns a new list which is sorted in ascending order. It does not modify the original list. It raises TypeError if the elements of the list are not comparable/heterogeneous.

# Aliasing: in python, if we assign a list to another variable, then both the variables will point to the same list in the memory. It is called aliasing. If we modify the list using one variable, then the changes will be reflected in the other variable.
# eg. list1=list2

# cloning: in python, if we want to create a new list which is a copy of the original list, then we can use the copy() method or we can use the slicing operator to create a new list. It is called cloning. If we modify the original list, then the changes will not be reflected in the cloned list.
# eg. list2=list1.copy() or list2=list1[:]
# in java, if we want to create a new list which is a copy of the original list, then we can use the constructor of the list to create a new list. It is called cloning. If we modify the original list, then the changes will not be reflected in the cloned list.
# eg. List<Integer> list2 = new ArrayList<>(list1) 
